## What Does a 0.75 Carat Princess Cut Diamond Cost in {{year}}?

The three-quarter carat princess cut sits in one of the most overlooked segments of the diamond market. At approximately $1,300–$1,750 for GIA-certified G-VS1 quality, it delivers dramatically more face-up diamond than the 0.5ct tier and costs meaningfully less than the 1ct tier — while being visually close to 1ct in daily wear.

I am **Farzana Hasan**, GIA-certified diamond expert and author of the [princess cut diamond buying guide](/princess-cut-diamond). The 0.75ct princess represents the best face-up-per-dollar value in the sub-1ct princess market. This guide gives you the exact numbers.

### The Decision Snapshot: 0.75ct Princess by Buyer Profile

| Buyer Profile | Recommended | Est. Price | Why |
|---------------|------------|-----------|-----|
| Maximum value | GIA 0.74ct G-VS2 princess | ~$1,280–$1,380 | Below magic threshold; identical look to 0.75ct |
| Sweet spot | GIA 0.75ct G-VS1 princess | ~$1,500–$1,750 | VS1 clarity; G minimum; safe and correct |
| Budget + look of 1ct | GIA 0.75ct F-VS1 princess | ~$1,600–$1,900 | F color adds visual brightness in white metals |
| Lab-grown upgrade | IGI 1ct D-VVS1 lab princess | ~$400–$600 | Same budget, 33% more face-up area |
| Best total ring | 0.75ct G-VS1 + V-prong 14K solitaire | ~$2,200–$2,700 | Full ring under $3K with quality stone |

